Description.LocalizedString: She stared out at a field of flowers, desperate to take her mind off those lost to the studio fire.
The blue and purple flowers were a soothing sight for her tired eyes. She breathed deep, taking in the crisp fall air.
Her future was uncertain in the wake of this tragedy. But for now, standing in that park, there was peace.
He salivated at the smell of sizzling street food and started at the sound of pounding drums, feeling both at home and like an outsider.
He squeezed through the cheering crowd just in time to watch the dancers in their ceremonial garb light up the moon house.
As the flames flickered against the night sky, Jake felt his grandfather's presence beckoning him to learn more about his heritage.
Her house was dark and silent as she entered. All she wanted was to gaze at the moon with her mom.
Her mother was still sleeping, her breathing frail. Rin swallowed her disappointment and unwrapped the mooncakes from the restaurant.
She watched the moon through the window, her mother's hand in her's, and she wished things could be different.
She gave the opponent to her right a quick nod and raced off, only to veer off the track and respawn back at the starting line.
Her avatar wiped out on a tight turn. She waited to respawn, watching her opponent navigate the racetrack with ease.
She lost once again. Her young opponent's braces sparkled as she smiled. They faced each other and bowed respectfully.
The expo was a hub-bub of gamers, devs, and marketers. A nearby booth showcasing the latest skateboarding game caught her eye.
She was nearly through the demo when she looked up and saw the security guard approaching, stencil in hand.
By the time the guard reached the booth, the only sign of her presence were the words "PERFECT SCORE" flashing on the screen.
The components were antiquated, circuits and electronics from a bygone era. And yet they appeared to be brand new.
The screens and lights were cosmetic, incidental to his pursuit for absolute perfection. Further tests would be required.
This form would serve his purpose, for now. Even so, he wondered how and why this body came to be in the first place.
Most of the singers bored him to tears, but an office worker with a bad haircut wowed the crowd with his vocal range.
He handed the office worker the trophy, and included a personal invitation to tour his studio.
That poor office worker was never seen again, but his voice was heard around the world months later.
She recalled running through the forest on a chilly autumn day, wiping her nose with her sleeve. Her cousins cheered as she leaped into a pile of leaves.
Her laughter faded as the stench of decay overwhelmed her. Beneath the leaves, she found the head of a deer staring blankly at the sky.
The creature was upon her, but she was frozen to the spot. She shed a tear as she waited to be consumed by the shambling nightmare.
Strumming the strings of her lute, she sang a tale from a faraway land where a lone moon shone.
The idea of another world seemed too fantastical to her audience, but her story of poems being read beneath the lone moon won them over.
As the crowd dispersed at the end of the night and she counted her earnings, Aestri couldn't help but watch the moons overhead.
The smells of burning flesh and plastic filled the air. There was no escape for him.
The fire spread down the side of his body, and he scurried away to hide.
The blade burned brightly, a perfect match for Chucky's fiery rage.
It was a captivating story. She wondered what it would be like to be in Maria's shoes, exploring an ancient Castle filled with sinister magic.
Deep in this Castle, Maria found Richter held under the sway of some greater, darker force.
They sang a ballad about a young woman named Maria searching an evil Castle for a man named Richter.
In her dream, she was sent to fight a great evil when a tragic fate befell her.
She was turned to a statue, trapped in time until discovered by a fellow warrior.
Mikaela awoke in her dark bedroom, searching frantically for her dream journal.
She imagined looking down from the ceiling, her many eyes blinking as she watched her captors enter the room.
She would scurry softly along the ceiling, ambushing them when there was no chance of escape.
She would feel the life drain from them slowly, painfully, until they stopped fighting back.
She turned on a desk lamp as the sky darkened. The wind rattled the windows, and she was thankful to be inside.
She tried to remember the last time she'd been outside just to enjoy the autumn weather. It was always her favorite season.
Lightning arced across the sky, accompanied by a shuddering boom moments later. The entire room went black, including her screen. Game over.
He played the fool as he took his seat, hiding his intentions behind his shades.
He let them get arrogant over the first few hands. He bided his time, studying the playstyles around the table.
None of the other players suspected he would clean them out, one by one, before the clock struck midnight.
He pointed at the old man and challenged him to step into the circle and prove himself.
Theold brute put up his fists, making feints and taunting David into striking first.
As a token of respect for putting up a good fight, the old man gave David the fighting gear from his glory days.
He imagined living on his own in the wilderness, scurrying, swimming, doing as he pleased.
His parents would be so shocked to find his room empty. He would watch from the trees as they searched for him.
He would make sure they felt as scared as him. And then he would strike.
